Two-center magnetic-multipole interaction between atoms, molecules, and nuclei

Ying-Nan ChiuCenter for Molecular Dynamics and Energy Transfer, Department of Chemistry, The Catholic University of America, Washington,D.C. 20064(Received 28 February 1979)

Abstract

A general formula in the form of a product of irreducible tensors is derived for the magnetic multipolemultipole interaction of any order between two nonoverlapping charge distributions. These two charge centers may be separate atoms, molecules, or nuclei. In the limit of low order, the formula is shown to reduce to the conventional spin-spin (magnetic dipole-dipole) interaction. It also reduces to a two-center exparsin term obtainable from the conventional spin-other-orbit interaction.

Although two-center expansion of electrostatic interaction has been well known, 1 − 13 1 − 13 ^(1-13){ }^{1-13}1−13 two-center expansion of magnetic interaction beyond the dipolar case has been scarce in literature, due in part possibly to mathematical complexity. One exception is the prolate-spheroidal expansions of the spin-orbit, spin-spin, and orbit-orbit operation by Matcha, Pritchard, and Kern. 14 14 ^(14){ }^{14}14 Such expansions are used mainly for the evaluation of molecular integrals 15 15 ^(15){ }^{15}15 in a diatomic molecule and are not expressed in terms of the usual magneticmultipole moments similar to those of multiple radiation fields. 15 − 20 15 − 20 ^(15-20){ }^{15-20}15−20 Such multipole moments in tensorial form are needed for the study of angularmomentum coupling and other symmetry properties of the interaction. The magnetic-multipole interaction for hyperfine structure such as that derived by Schwart 21 21 ^(21){ }^{21}21 and later by others 19 19 ^(19){ }^{19}19 is a one-center expansion applicable to the interaction of the atomic electron with the same atom's nuclear electric and magnetic moments. 22 22 ^(22){ }^{22}22 The present work is to derive the two-center magneticmultipole interaction of any order in irreducible tensorial form. It can be used for example in the mixed higher electric- and magnetic-multipole dispersion interaction 23 − 25 23 − 25 ^(23-25){ }^{23-25}23−25 between two (sometimes optically active) molecular radicals with nonvanishing spin ( S ) ( S ) (S)(S)(S) and orbital ( L ) ( L ) (L)(L)(L) angular momentum. It will also lead to the formula for nuclear octopole-octopole interaction 25 25 ^(25){ }^{25}25 between two neighboring nuclei (for example, 26 − 28 26 − 28 ^(26-28){ }^{26-28}26−28 in B r 79 , B r 81 B r 79 , B r 81 Br^(79),Br^(81)\mathrm{Br}^{79}, \mathrm{Br}^{81}Br79,Br81 and In 115 , I 127 In 115 , I 127 In^(115),I^(127)\operatorname{In}^{115}, \mathrm{I}^{127}In115,I127, etc.).
